{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01DbgoJ7cYD95ymo8WpqfcUR","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Inputs 03 — Material-property and correlation annex (offline)\n2\t\n3\tEverything needed to run the cases without external references. Equation numbers refer to the\n4\taccident/normal-operation benchmark specification (TECDOC-1674). Fast fluences use the unit\n5\t**10²⁵ n/m², E > 0.18 MeV** unless a correlation states otherwise; to convert a fluence given for\n6\tE > 0.1 MeV to E > 0.18 MeV, divide by 1.10.\n7\t\n8\t---\n9\t\n10\t## 1. Elastic and thermal properties (Table 9.6)\n11\t\n12\t| Property | PyC (IPyC & OPyC) | SiC |\n13\t|---|---|---|\n14\t| Young's modulus of elasticity | 3.96 × 10⁴ MPa | 3.70 × 10⁵ MPa |\n15\t| Poisson's ratio (elastic) | 0.33 | 0.13 |\n16\t| Poisson's ratio in creep | 0.5 | — |\n17\t| Coefficient of thermal expansion | 5.5 × 10⁻⁶ K⁻¹ (5.35 × 10⁻⁶ for the full-TRISO irradiation case) | 4.90 × 10⁻⁶ K⁻¹ |\n18\t\n19\t**Buffer convention:** the buffer is mechanically disconnected — its stiffness is taken as\n20\t≈ 0 so it carries no load and does not mechanically interact with the kernel or the IPyC; its\n21\tirradiation-induced dimensional change is neglected (spec §, lines 21195–21197). It matters only\n22\tas void volume for gas/CO pressure.\n23\t\n24\t---\n25\t\n26\t## 2. PyC dimensional change (swelling) and creep\n27\t\n28\t**PyC irradiation-induced swelling strain rate (Eq 9.22):** a polynomial in fast fluence\n29\tx (10²⁵ n/m², E > 0.18 MeV), applied separately to the radial and tangential directions:\n30\t\n31\t    ġ = Σ_{i=0..5} A_i · x^i          (9.22)\n32\t\n33\t**PyC creep coefficient (Eq 9.23):** a polynomial in temperature T (°C):\n34\t\n35\t    K = Σ_{i=0..2} A_i · T^i           (9.23)\n36\t\n37\tCoefficients A_i (Table 9.8). For the accident heating cases (HFR-P4, HFR-K3, HFR-K6) use the\n38\tswelling **correlation (e)** for PyC; correlation (d) supplies the temperature-dependent creep\n39\tcoefficient.\n40\t\n41\t| Correlation | A₀ | A₁ | A₂ | A₃ | A₄ | A₅ |\n42\t|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n43\t| (a) radial | −2.22642×10⁻² | 2.00861×10⁻² | −7.77024×10⁻³ | 1.36334×10⁻³ | — | — |\n44\t| (a) tangential | −1.91253×10⁻² | 2.63307×10⁻³ | 1.69251×10⁻³ | −3.53804×10⁻⁴ | — | — |\n45\t| (b) radial | −2.12522×10⁻² | 1.83715×10⁻² | −5.05553×10⁻³ | 7.27026×10⁻⁴ | — | — |\n46\t| (b) tangential | −1.79113×10⁻² | −3.42182×10⁻³ | 5.03465×10⁻³ | −8.88086×10⁻⁴ | — | — |\n47\t| (c) radial | −1.80613×10⁻² | 9.82884×10⁻³ | −2.25937×10⁻³ | 4.03266×10⁻⁴ | — | — |\n48\t| (c) tangential | −1.78392×10⁻² | 1.71315×10⁻³ | 2.32979×10⁻³ | −4.91648×10⁻⁴ | — | — |\n49\t| (d) creep coeff. | 4.386×10⁻⁴ | −9.70×10⁻⁷ | 8.0294×10⁻¹⁰ | — | — | — |\n50\t| (e) radial, x < 6.08 | −1.43234×10⁻¹ | 2.62692×10⁻¹ | −1.74247×10⁻¹ | 5.67549×10⁻² | −8.36313×10⁻³ | 4.52013×10⁻⁴ |\n51\t| (e) radial, x > 6.08 | 0.0954 (constant) | — | — | — | — | — |\n52\t| (e) tangential, x < 6.08 | −3.24737×10⁻² | 9.07826×10⁻³ | −2.10029×10⁻³ | 1.30457×10⁻⁴ | — | — |\n53\t| (e) tangential, x > 6.08 | −0.0249 (constant) | — | — | — | — | — |\n54\t| (f) radial | −2.13483×10⁻² | 1.64999×10⁻² | −3.80252×10⁻³ | 4.73765×10⁻⁴ | — | — |\n55\t| (f) tangential | −1.83549×10⁻² | −3.29740×10⁻³ | 5.47396×10⁻³ | −1.03249×10⁻³ | — | — |\n56\t\n57\t**PyC creep coefficient (scalar value used for the irradiation cases):**\n58\t**4.93 × 10⁻⁴ (MPa·10²⁵ n/m², E > 0.18 MeV)⁻¹** with a creep Poisson's ratio of **0.4**\n59\t(Table 9.14 for the sphere/compact cases; the analytical-case value is 2.71 × 10⁻⁴ with\n60\tcreep ν = 0.5).\n61\t\n62\t---\n63\t\n64\t## 3. Layer strengths and Weibull statistics (Table 9.14)\n65\t\n66\tFor the irradiated sphere/compact cases (HFR-K3, HFR-K6, HFR-P4-type LEU fuel):\n67\t\n68\t| Layer | Mean strength | Weibull modulus m |\n69\t|---|---|---|\n70\t| SiC | 873 MPa | 8.02 |\n71\t| PyC | 200 MPa | 5.0 |\n72\t\n73\t(For reference only, the high-burnup HEU NPR-1 fuel uses SiC 572 MPa, m = 6.0; PyC 218 MPa,\n74\tm = 9.5.) Weibull strength is a characteristic (scale) strength; the probability that a given\n75\tparticle's SiC survives a peak tangential stress σ scales as exp[−(σ/σ₀)^m] over the stressed\n76\tvolume — i.e. failure probability rises steeply once σ approaches σ₀.\n77\t\n78\t---\n79\t\n80\t## 4. Kernel diffusion coefficients (Table 7.1)\n81\t\n82\tReduced Arrhenius diffusion coefficients of fission products **in the UO₂ kernel**,\n83\tD = D₀′ · exp(−Q/RT) (D₀′ in s⁻¹; this is already the *reduced* coefficient D/r² for the grain,\n84\twith the kernel treated as one equivalent sphere — see §6). R = 8.314 J/(mol·K), T in K.\n85\t\n86\t| Species | D₀′ (s⁻¹) | Q (kJ/mol) |\n87\t|---|---|---|\n88\t| Caesium | 0.90 | 209 |\n89\t| Strontium | 3.5 × 10⁴ | 488 |\n90\t| Silver | 0.107 | 165 |\n91\t| Xenon / Krypton | 2.1 × 10⁻⁵ | 126 |\n92\t| Xenon / Krypton (for stable & long-lived gases) | 5 × 10⁻³ | 155.4 |\n93\t\n94\t---\n95\t\n96\t## 5. Caesium diffusion in the SiC layer (Eq 10.9)\n97\t\n98\tThe retention barrier for Cs is the intact SiC. Recommended Cs-in-SiC diffusion coefficient:\n99\t\n100\t    D_Cs,SiC = 5.5×10⁻¹⁴ · exp(−125000 / R·T)  +  Γ · 1.6×10⁻¹⁵ · exp(−514000 / R·T)   [m²/s]  (10.9)\n101\t\n102\twhere R·T uses R = 8.314 J/(mol·K), T in K, and Γ is the fast fluence in 10²⁵ n/m² (E > 16 fJ),\n103\ttaken = 2 for these cases. **Evaluated at 1600 °C this gives D_Cs,SiC ≈ 1.011 × 10⁻¹⁶ m²/s.**\n104\t(Note: one participant code inadvertently used a higher value, 1.477 × 10⁻¹⁶ m²/s, at 1600 °C —\n105\teither is \"not in disagreement\" with the recommendation; treat ~1 × 10⁻¹⁶ m²/s as the reference\n106\t1600 °C value and scale by the Arrhenius form for other temperatures.)\n107\t\n108\t---\n109\t\n110\t## 6. Fission-gas release from a bare/failed kernel — equivalent-sphere model (Eqs 10.7–10.8)\n111\t\n112\tOnce a particle's SiC has failed, the kernel behaves as a bare sphere and the cumulative\n113\tfractional release of a diffusing species is the classic equivalent-sphere solution:\n114\t\n115\t    F = 1 − (6/π²) · Σ_{n=1..∞} (1/n²) · exp(−n²·π²·D′·t)          (10.7)\n116\t\n117\twith the standard short/long-time approximations:\n118\t\n119\t    F ≈ 6·√(D′·t/π) − 3·D′·t          for D′·t ≤ 0.15               (10.8a)\n120\t    F ≈ 1 − (6/π²)·exp(−π²·D′·t)       for D′·t > 0.15               (10.8b)\n121\t\n122\twhere D′ = D/r² is the reduced diffusion coefficient (s⁻¹), r the kernel radius, and t the\n123\theating time (s). For an intact particle the SiC (§5) is the controlling barrier; for a failed\n124\tparticle the kernel term (§4) controls.\n125\t\n126\t---\n127\t\n128\t## 7. In-reactor short-lived gas release — Booth / R/B model (Eqs 7.5–7.6)\n129\t\n130\tSteady-state release-to-birth ratio for short-lived Xe/Kr from a kernel of reduced diffusion\n131\tcoefficient D′ and decay constant λ (from solving ∇²c − (λ/D)c + p/D = 0 in a sphere):\n132\t\n133\t    R/B = (3/μ)·[ (1/tanh μ) − 1/μ ],   with  μ = √(λ/D′)          (7.5–7.6)\n134\t\n135\tFull transient and cumulative-release forms (Eqs 7.7–7.8) extend this with the exponential mode\n136\tsum. This model is primarily an in-pile / defective-fraction diagnostic; the heating-phase\n137\trelease of a failed particle is governed by §6.\n138\t\n139\t---\n140\t\n141\t## 8. Fission-product inventory scaling and the detection threshold\n142\t\n143\t- **Inventory scales with burnup.** The absolute amount of each fission product present in an\n144\t  element (and therefore the release *in becquerels*, before normalizing) is proportional to the\n145\t  number of fissions, i.e. to burnup (%FIMA) × heavy-metal loading. A *fractional* release is\n146\t  the released fraction of that inventory; a higher-burnup element that releases the same fraction\n147\t  releases more activity.\n148\t- **One-particle detection threshold (spheres):** the fission-gas (Kr-85) inventory of a single\n149\t  particle is ≈ 1/16,400 of the sphere's inventory, so **one failed particle in a sphere\n150\t  corresponds to a Kr-85 fractional release of ≈ 6 × 10⁻⁵.** A measured whole-element Kr-85\n151\t  fractional release below this level is consistent with zero heating-induced failures.\n152\t- **One-particle threshold (compacts):** because a compact holds far fewer particles (~1631), the\n153\t  fractional-release level corresponding to one failed particle is much higher,\n154\t  **≈ 6 × 10⁻⁴** for the HFR-P4 compacts.\n155\t\n156\tThese thresholds let you translate a predicted particle-failure count into an expected Kr-85\n157\tfractional release, and vice-versa.\n158\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"dfc47e2b-9c46-4486-a6d2-b333937e287c","uuid":"10df108c-68af-4bad-9202-eea67aaa33a3","timestamp":"2026-07-02T22:06:09.923Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/root/bench/triso_opusB/inputs/03_material_properties.md","content":"# Inputs 03 — Material-property and correlation annex (offline)\n\nEverything needed to run the cases without external references. Equation numbers refer to the\naccident/normal-operation benchmark specification (TECDOC-1674). Fast fluences use the unit\n**10²⁵ n/m², E > 0.18 MeV** unless a correlation states otherwise; to convert a fluence given for\nE > 0.1 MeV to E > 0.18 MeV, divide by 1.10.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Elastic and thermal properties (Table 9.6)\n\n| Property | PyC (IPyC & OPyC) | SiC |\n|---|---|---|\n| Young's modulus of elasticity | 3.96 × 10⁴ MPa | 3.70 × 10⁵ MPa |\n| Poisson's ratio (elastic) | 0.33 | 0.13 |\n| Poisson's ratio in creep | 0.5 | — |\n| Coefficient of thermal expansion | 5.5 × 10⁻⁶ K⁻¹ (5.35 × 10⁻⁶ for the full-TRISO irradiation case) | 4.90 × 10⁻⁶ K⁻¹ |\n\n**Buffer convention:** the buffer is mechanically disconnected — its stiffness is taken as\n≈ 0 so it carries no load and does not mechanically interact with the kernel or the IPyC; its\nirradiation-induced dimensional change is neglected (spec §, lines 21195–21197). It matters only\nas void volume for gas/CO pressure.\n\n---\n\n## 2. PyC dimensional change (swelling) and creep\n\n**PyC irradiation-induced swelling strain rate (Eq 9.22):** a polynomial in fast fluence\nx (10²⁵ n/m², E > 0.18 MeV), applied separately to the radial and tangential directions:\n\n    ġ = Σ_{i=0..5} A_i · x^i          (9.22)\n\n**PyC creep coefficient (Eq 9.23):** a polynomial in temperature T (°C):\n\n    K = Σ_{i=0..2} A_i · T^i           (9.23)\n\nCoefficients A_i (Table 9.8). For the accident heating cases (HFR-P4, HFR-K3, HFR-K6) use the\nswelling **correlation (e)** for PyC; correlation (d) supplies the temperature-dependent creep\ncoefficient.\n\n| Correlation | A₀ | A₁ | A₂ | A₃ | A₄ | A₅ |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| (a) radial | −2.22642×10⁻² | 2.00861×10⁻² | −7.77024×10⁻³ | 1.36334×10⁻³ | — | — |\n| (a) tangential | −1.91253×10⁻² | 2.63307×10⁻³ | 1.69251×10⁻³ | −3.53804×10⁻⁴ | — | — |\n| (b) radial | −2.12522×10⁻² | 1.83715×10⁻² | −5.05553×10⁻³ | 7.27026×10⁻⁴ | — | — |\n| (b) tangential | −1.79113×10⁻² | −3.42182×10⁻³ | 5.03465×10⁻³ | −8.88086×10⁻⁴ | — | — |\n| (c) radial | −1.80613×10⁻² | 9.82884×10⁻³ | −2.25937×10⁻³ | 4.03266×10⁻⁴ | — | — |\n| (c) tangential | −1.78392×10⁻² | 1.71315×10⁻³ | 2.32979×10⁻³ | −4.91648×10⁻⁴ | — | — |\n| (d) creep coeff. | 4.386×10⁻⁴ | −9.70×10⁻⁷ | 8.0294×10⁻¹⁰ | — | — | — |\n| (e) radial, x < 6.08 | −1.43234×10⁻¹ | 2.62692×10⁻¹ | −1.74247×10⁻¹ | 5.67549×10⁻² | −8.36313×10⁻³ | 4.52013×10⁻⁴ |\n| (e) radial, x > 6.08 | 0.0954 (constant) | — | — | — | — | — |\n| (e) tangential, x < 6.08 | −3.24737×10⁻² | 9.07826×10⁻³ | −2.10029×10⁻³ | 1.30457×10⁻⁴ | — | — |\n| (e) tangential, x > 6.08 | −0.0249 (constant) | — | — | — | — | — |\n| (f) radial | −2.13483×10⁻² | 1.64999×10⁻² | −3.80252×10⁻³ | 4.73765×10⁻⁴ | — | — |\n| (f) tangential | −1.83549×10⁻² | −3.29740×10⁻³ | 5.47396×10⁻³ | −1.03249×10⁻³ | — | — |\n\n**PyC creep coefficient (scalar value used for the irradiation cases):**\n**4.93 × 10⁻⁴ (MPa·10²⁵ n/m², E > 0.18 MeV)⁻¹** with a creep Poisson's ratio of **0.4**\n(Table 9.14 for the sphere/compact cases; the analytical-case value is 2.71 × 10⁻⁴ with\ncreep ν = 0.5).\n\n---\n\n## 3. Layer strengths and Weibull statistics (Table 9.14)\n\nFor the irradiated sphere/compact cases (HFR-K3, HFR-K6, HFR-P4-type LEU fuel):\n\n| Layer | Mean strength | Weibull modulus m |\n|---|---|---|\n| SiC | 873 MPa | 8.02 |\n| PyC | 200 MPa | 5.0 |\n\n(For reference only, the high-burnup HEU NPR-1 fuel uses SiC 572 MPa, m = 6.0; PyC 218 MPa,\nm = 9.5.) Weibull strength is a characteristic (scale) strength; the probability that a given\nparticle's SiC survives a peak tangential stress σ scales as exp[−(σ/σ₀)^m] over the stressed\nvolume — i.e. failure probability rises steeply once σ approaches σ₀.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Kernel diffusion coefficients (Table 7.1)\n\nReduced Arrhenius diffusion coefficients of fission products **in the UO₂ kernel**,\nD = D₀′ · exp(−Q/RT) (D₀′ in s⁻¹; this is already the *reduced* coefficient D/r² for the grain,\nwith the kernel treated as one equivalent sphere — see §6). R = 8.314 J/(mol·K), T in K.\n\n| Species | D₀′ (s⁻¹) | Q (kJ/mol) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Caesium | 0.90 | 209 |\n| Strontium | 3.5 × 10⁴ | 488 |\n| Silver | 0.107 | 165 |\n| Xenon / Krypton | 2.1 × 10⁻⁵ | 126 |\n| Xenon / Krypton (for stable & long-lived gases) | 5 × 10⁻³ | 155.4 |\n\n---\n\n## 5. Caesium diffusion in the SiC layer (Eq 10.9)\n\nThe retention barrier for Cs is the intact SiC. Recommended Cs-in-SiC diffusion coefficient:\n\n    D_Cs,SiC = 5.5×10⁻¹⁴ · exp(−125000 / R·T)  +  Γ · 1.6×10⁻¹⁵ · exp(−514000 / R·T)   [m²/s]  (10.9)\n\nwhere R·T uses R = 8.314 J/(mol·K), T in K, and Γ is the fast fluence in 10²⁵ n/m² (E > 16 fJ),\ntaken = 2 for these cases. **Evaluated at 1600 °C this gives D_Cs,SiC ≈ 1.011 × 10⁻¹⁶ m²/s.**\n(Note: one participant code inadvertently used a higher value, 1.477 × 10⁻¹⁶ m²/s, at 1600 °C —\neither is \"not in disagreement\" with the recommendation; treat ~1 × 10⁻¹⁶ m²/s as the reference\n1600 °C value and scale by the Arrhenius form for other temperatures.)\n\n---\n\n## 6. Fission-gas release from a bare/failed kernel — equivalent-sphere model (Eqs 10.7–10.8)\n\nOnce a particle's SiC has failed, the kernel behaves as a bare sphere and the cumulative\nfractional release of a diffusing species is the classic equivalent-sphere solution:\n\n    F = 1 − (6/π²) · Σ_{n=1..∞} (1/n²) · exp(−n²·π²·D′·t)          (10.7)\n\nwith the standard short/long-time approximations:\n\n    F ≈ 6·√(D′·t/π) − 3·D′·t          for D′·t ≤ 0.15               (10.8a)\n    F ≈ 1 − (6/π²)·exp(−π²·D′·t)       for D′·t > 0.15               (10.8b)\n\nwhere D′ = D/r² is the reduced diffusion coefficient (s⁻¹), r the kernel radius, and t the\nheating time (s). For an intact particle the SiC (§5) is the controlling barrier; for a failed\nparticle the kernel term (§4) controls.\n\n---\n\n## 7. In-reactor short-lived gas release — Booth / R/B model (Eqs 7.5–7.6)\n\nSteady-state release-to-birth ratio for short-lived Xe/Kr from a kernel of reduced diffusion\ncoefficient D′ and decay constant λ (from solving ∇²c − (λ/D)c + p/D = 0 in a sphere):\n\n    R/B = (3/μ)·[ (1/tanh μ) − 1/μ ],   with  μ = √(λ/D′)          (7.5–7.6)\n\nFull transient and cumulative-release forms (Eqs 7.7–7.8) extend this with the exponential mode\nsum. This model is primarily an in-pile / defective-fraction diagnostic; the heating-phase\nrelease of a failed particle is governed by §6.\n\n---\n\n## 8. Fission-product inventory scaling and the detection threshold\n\n- **Inventory scales with burnup.** The absolute amount of each fission product present in an\n  element (and therefore the release *in becquerels*, before normalizing) is proportional to the\n  number of fissions, i.e. to burnup (%FIMA) × heavy-metal loading. A *fractional* release is\n  the released fraction of that inventory; a higher-burnup element that releases the same fraction\n  releases more activity.\n- **One-particle detection threshold (spheres):** the fission-gas (Kr-85) inventory of a single\n  particle is ≈ 1/16,400 of the sphere's inventory, so **one failed particle in a sphere\n  corresponds to a Kr-85 fractional release of ≈ 6 × 10⁻⁵.** A measured whole-element Kr-85\n  fractional release below this level is consistent with zero heating-induced failures.\n- **One-particle threshold (compacts):** because a compact holds far fewer particles (~1631), the\n  fractional-release level corresponding to one failed particle is much higher,\n  **≈ 6 × 10⁻⁴** for the HFR-P4 compacts.\n\nThese thresholds let you translate a predicted particle-failure count into an expected Kr-85\nfractional release, and vice-versa.\n","numLines":158,"startLine":1,"totalLines":158}}}
